# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adipocyte
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Prokaryotes and plants have multi-subunit ACCs composed of several polypeptides.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Biotin carboxylase (BC) activity, biotin carboxyl carrier protein (BCCP), and carboxyl transferase (CT) activity are each contained on a different subunit.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The stoichiometry of these subunits in the ACC holoenzyme differs amongst organisms.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Humans and most eukaryotes have evolved an ACC with CT and BC catalytic domains and BCCP domains on a single polypeptide.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Most plants also have this homomeric form in cytosol.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] ACC functional regions, starting from the N-terminus to C-terminus are the biotin carboxylase (BC), biotin binding (BB), carboxyl transferase (CT), and ATP-binding (AB).
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Biotin is covalently attached through an amide bond to the long side chain of a lysine reside in BB.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] As BB is between BC and CT regions, biotin can easily translocate to both of the active sites where it is required.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] In mammals where two isoforms of ACC are expressed, the main structural difference between these isoforms is the extended ACC2 N-terminus containing a mitochondrial targeting sequence.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The polypeptides composing the multi-subunit ACCs of prokaryotes and plants are encoded by distinct genes.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] In *Escherichia coli*, *accA* encodes the alpha subunit of the acetyl-CoA carboxylase, and *accD* encodes its beta subunit.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The overall reaction of ACAC(A,B) proceeds by a two-step mechanism.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The first reaction is carried out by BC and involves the ATP-dependent carboxylation of biotin with bicarbonate serving as the source of CO2.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The carboxyl group is transferred from biotin to acetyl-CoA to form malonyl-CoA in the second reaction, which is catalyzed by CT.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] In the active site, the reaction proceeds with extensive interaction of the residues Glu296 and positively charged Arg338 and Arg292 with the substrates.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Two Mg2+ are coordinated by the phosphate groups on the ATP, and are required for ATP binding to the enzyme.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Bicarbonate is deprotonated by Glu296, although in solution, this proton transfer is unlikely as the p*K*a of bicarbonate is 10.3.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The enzyme apparently manipulates the pKa to facilitate the deprotonation of bicarbonate.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The p*K*a of bicarbonate is decreased by its interaction with positively charged side chains of Arg338 and Arg292.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Furthermore, Glu296 interacts with the side chain of Glu211, an interaction that has been shown to cause an increase in the apparent pKa.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Following deprotonation of bicarbonate, the oxygen of the bicarbonate acts as a nucleophile and attacks the gamma phosphate on ATP.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The carboxyphosphate intermediate quickly decomposes to CO2 and PO3−4.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The PO3−4 deprotonates biotin, creating an enolate, stabilized by Arg338, that subsequently attacks CO2 resulting in the production of carboxybiotin.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The carboxybiotin translocates to the carboxyl transferase (CT) active site, where the carboxyl group is transferred to acetyl-CoA.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] In contrast to the BC domain, little is known about the reaction mechanism of CT.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] A proposed mechanism is the release of CO2 from biotin, which subsequently abstracts a proton from the methyl group from acetyl-CoA carboxylase.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The resulting enolate attacks CO2 to form malonyl-CoA.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] In a competing mechanism, proton abstraction is concerted with the attack of acetyl-CoA.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The function of ACC is to regulate the metabolism of fatty acids.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] When the enzyme is active, the product, malonyl-CoA, is produced which is a building block for new fatty acids and can inhibit the transfer of the fatty acyl group from acyl-CoA to carnitine with carnitine acyltransferase, which inhibits the beta-oxidation of fatty acids in the mitochondria.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] In mammals, two main isoforms of ACC are expressed, ACC1 and ACC2, which differ in both tissue distribution and function.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] ACC1 is found in the cytoplasm of all cells but is enriched in lipogenic tissue, such as adipose tissue and lactating mammary glands, where fatty acid synthesis is important.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] In oxidative tissues, such as the skeletal muscle and the heart, the ratio of ACC2 expressed is higher.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] ACC1 and ACC2 are both highly expressed in the liver where both fatty acid oxidation and synthesis are important.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The differences in tissue distribution indicate that ACC1 maintains regulation of fatty acid synthesis whereas ACC2 mainly regulates fatty acid oxidation (beta oxidation).
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] A mitochondrial isoform of ACC1 (mtACC1) plays a partially redundant role in lipoic acid synthesis and thus in protein lipoylation by providing malonyl-CoA for mitochondrial fatty acid synthesis (mtFAS) in tandem with ACSF3.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The regulation of mammalian ACC is complex, in order to control two distinct pools of malonyl-CoA that direct either the inhibition of beta oxidation or the activation of lipid biosynthesis.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Mammalian ACC1 and ACC2 are regulated transcriptionally by multiple promoters which mediate ACC abundance in response to the cells nutritional status.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Activation of gene expression through different promoters results in alternative splicing; however, the physiological significance of specific ACC isozymes remains unclear.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The sensitivity to nutritional status results from the control of these promoters by transcription factors such as sterol regulatory element-binding protein 1, controlled by insulin at the transcriptional level, and ChREBP, which increases in expression with high carbohydrates diets.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Through a feed-forward loop, citrate allosterically activates ACC.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Citrate may increase ACC polymerization to increase enzymatic activity; however, it is unclear if polymerization is citrate's main mechanism of increasing ACC activity or if polymerization is an artifact of in vitro experiments.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Other allosteric activators include glutamate and other dicarboxylic acids.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Long and short chain fatty acyl-CoAs are negative feedback inhibitors of ACC.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] One such negative allosteric modulator is palmitoyl-CoA.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Phosphorylation can result when the hormones glucagon or epinephrine bind to cell surface receptors, but the main cause of phosphorylation is due to a rise in AMP levels when the energy status of the cell is low, leading to the activation of the AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK).
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] AMPK is the main kinase regulator of ACC, able to phosphorylate a number of serine residues on both isoforms of ACC.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] On ACC1, AMPK phosphorylates Ser79, Ser1200, and Ser1215.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Protein kinase A also has the ability to phosphorylate ACC, with a much greater ability to phosphorylate ACC2 than ACC1.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Ser80 and Ser1263 on ACC1 may also serve as a site of phosphorylation as a regulatory mechanism.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] However, the physiological significance of protein kinase A in the regulation of ACC is currently unknown.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Researchers hypothesize there are other ACC kinases important to its regulation as there are many other possible phosphorylation sites on ACC.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] When insulin binds to its receptors on the cellular membrane, it activates a phosphatase enzyme called protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A) to dephosphorylate the enzyme; thereby removing the inhibitory effect.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Furthermore, insulin induces a phosphodiesterase that lowers the level of cAMP in the cell, thus inhibiting PKA, and also inhibits AMPK directly.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] This protein may use the morpheein model of allosteric regulation.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] At the juncture of lipid synthesis and oxidation pathways, ACC presents many clinical possibilities for the production of novel antibiotics and the development of new therapies for diabetes, obesity, and other manifestations of metabolic syndrome.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Researchers aim to take advantage of structural differences between bacterial and human ACCs to create antibiotics specific to the bacterial ACC, in efforts to minimize side effects to patients.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Promising results for the usefulness of an ACC inhibitor include the finding that mice with no expression of ACC2 have continuous fatty acid oxidation, reduced body fat mass, and reduced body weight despite an increase in food consumption.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] These mice are also protected from diabetes.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] A lack of ACC1 in mutant mice is lethal already at the embryonic stage.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] However, it is unknown whether drugs targeting ACCs in humans must be specific for ACC2.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Firsocostat (formerly GS-976, ND-630, NDI-010976) is a potent allosteric ACC inhibitor, acting at the BC domain of ACC.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] Firsocostat is under development in 2019 (Phase II) by the pharmaceutical company Gilead as part of a combination treatment for non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH), believed to be an increasing cause of liver failure.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] In addition, plant-selective ACC inhibitors are in widespread use as herbicides, which suggests clinical application against Apicomplexa parasites that rely on a plant-derived ACC isoform, including malaria.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] ACC inhibitors in IRAC group 23 are used as insecticides / acaricides.
[src:adipocyte/acetyl-coa-carboxylase] The heterogeneous clinical phenotypes of the metabolic disease combined malonic and methylmalonic aciduria (CMAMMA) due to ACSF3 deficiency are thought to result from partial compensation of a mitochondrial isoform of ACC1 (mtACC1) for deficient ACSF3 in mitochondrial fatty acid synthesis (mtFAS).
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] There are two types of adipose tissue, white adipose tissue (WAT) and brown adipose tissue (BAT), which are also known as white and brown fat, respectively, and comprise two types of fat cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] White fat cells contain a single large lipid droplet surrounded by a layer of cytoplasm, and are known as unilocular.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] The nucleus is flattened and pushed to the periphery.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] A typical fat cell is 0.1 mm in diameter with some being twice that size, and others half that size.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] However, these numerical estimates of fat cell size depend largely on the measurement method and the location of the adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] The fat stored is in a semi-liquid state, and is composed primarily of triglycerides, and cholesteryl ester.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] White fat cells secrete many proteins acting as adipokines such as resistin, adiponectin, leptin and apelin.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] An average human adult has 30 billion fat cells with a weight of 30 lbs or 13.5 kg.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] If a child or adolescent gains sufficient excess weight, fat cells may increase in absolute number until age twenty-four.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] A large meta-analysis has shown that white adipose tissue cell size is dependent on measurement methods, adipose tissue depots, age, and body mass index; for the same degree of obesity, increases in fat cell size were also associated with the dysregulations in glucose and lipid metabolism.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Brown fat cells are polyhedral in shape.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Brown fat is derived from dermatomyocyte cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Unlike white fat cells, these cells have considerable cytoplasm, with several lipid droplets scattered throughout, and are known as multilocular cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] The nucleus is round and, although eccentrically located, it is not in the periphery of the cell.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] The brown color comes from the large quantity of mitochondria.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Brown fat, also known as "baby fat," is used to generate heat.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Marrow adipocytes are unilocular like white fat cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] The marrow adipose tissue depot is poorly understood in terms of its physiologic function and relevance to bone health.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Marrow adipose tissue expands in states of low bone density but additionally expands in the setting of obesity.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Marrow adipose tissue response to exercise approximates that of white adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Exercise reduces both adipocyte size as well as marrow adipose tissue volume, as quantified by MRI or μCT imaging of bone stained with the lipid binder osmium.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Mesenchymal stem cells can differentiate into adipocytes, connective tissue, muscle or bone.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] The precursor of the adult cell is termed a lipoblast, and a tumor of this cell type is known as a lipoblastoma.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Fat cells in some mice have been shown to drop in count due to fasting and other properties were observed when exposed to cold.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] If the adipocytes in the body reach their maximum capacity of fat, they may replicate to allow additional fat storage.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] According to some reports and textbooks, the number of adipocytes can increase in childhood and adolescence, though the amount is usually constant in adults.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Individuals who become obese as adults, rather than as adolescents, have no more adipocytes than they had before.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Body fat cells have regional responses to the overfeeding that was studied in adult subjects.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] In the upper body, an increase of adipocyte size correlated with upper-body fat gain; however, the number of fat cells was not significantly changed.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] In contrast to the upper body fat cell response, the number of lower-body adipocytes did significantly increase during the course of experiment.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Notably, there was no change in the size of the lower-body adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Approximately 10% of fat cells are renewed annually at all adult ages and levels of body mass index without a significant increase in the overall number of adipocytes in adulthood.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Obesity is characterized by the expansion of fat mass, through adipocyte size increase (hypertrophy) and, to a lesser extent, cell proliferation (hyperplasia).
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] In the fatty tissue of obese individuals, there is increased production of metabolism modulators, such as glycerol, hormones, macrophage-stimulating chemokines, and pro-inflammatory cytokines, leading to the development of insulin resistance.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Production of these modulators and the resulting pathogenesis of insulin resistance are probably caused by adipocytes as well as immune system macrophages that infiltrate the tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Fat production in adipocytes is strongly stimulated by insulin.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] By controlling the activity of the pyruvate dehydrogenase and the acetyl-CoA carboxylase enzymes, insulin promotes unsaturated fatty acid synthesis.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] It also promotes glucose uptake and induces SREBF1, which activates the transcription of genes that stimulate lipogenesis.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] SREBF1 (sterol regulatory element-binding transcription factor 1) is a transcription factor synthesized as an inactive precursor protein inserted into the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) membrane by two membrane-spanning helices.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Also anchored in the ER membrane is SCAP (SREBF-cleavage activating protein), which binds SREBF1.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] The SREBF1-SCAP complex is retained in the ER membrane by INSIG1 (insulin-induced gene 1 protein).
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] When sterol levels are depleted, INSIG1 releases SCAP and the SREBF1-SCAP complex can be sorted into transport vesicles coated by the coatomer COPII that are exported to the Golgi apparatus.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] In the Golgi apparatus, SREBF1 is cleaved and released as a transcriptionally active mature protein.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] It is then free to translocate to the nucleus and activate the expression of its target genes.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Clinical studies have repeatedly shown that even though insulin resistance is usually associated with obesity, the membrane phospholipids of the adipocytes of obese patients generally still show an increased degree of fatty acid unsaturation.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] This seems to point to an adaptive mechanism that allows the adipocyte to maintain its functionality, despite the increased storage demands associated with obesity and insulin resistance.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] A study conducted in 2013 found that, while INSIG1 and SREBF1 mRNA expression was decreased in the adipose tissue of obese mice and humans, the amount of active SREBF1 was increased in comparison with normal mice and non-obese patients.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] This downregulation of INSIG1 expression combined with the increase of mature SREBF1 was also correlated with the maintenance of SREBF1-target gene expression.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Hence, it appears that, by downregulating INSIG1, there is a resetting of the INSIG1/SREBF1 loop, allowing for the maintenance of active SREBF1 levels.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] This seems to help compensate for the anti-lipogenic effects of insulin resistance and thus preserve adipocyte fat storage abilities and availability of appropriate levels of fatty acid unsaturation in face of the nutritional pressures of obesity.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Adipocytes can synthesize estrogens from androgens, potentially being the reason why being underweight or overweight are risk factors for infertility.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Additionally, adipocytes are responsible for the production of the hormone leptin.
[src:adipocyte/adipocyte] Leptin is important in regulation of appetite and acts as a satiety factor.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Adipocytes play a vital role in energy homeostasis and process the largest energy reserve as triglycerol in the body of animals.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Adipocytes stay in a dynamic state, they start expanding when the energy intake is higher than the expenditure and undergo mobilization when the energy expenditure exceeds the intake.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] This process is highly regulated by counter regulatory hormones to which these cells are very sensitive.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] The hormone insulin promotes expansion whereas the counter hormones epinephrine, glucagon, and ACTH promote mobilization.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Adipogenesis is a tightly regulated cellular differentiation process, in which mesenchymal stem cells committing to preadipocytes and preadipocytes differentiating into adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Cellular differentiation is a change of gene expression patterns which multipotent gene expression alters to cell type specific gene expression.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Therefore, transcription factors are crucial for adipogenesis.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Transcription factors, peroxis proliferator-activated receptor γ (PPARγ) and CCAAT enhancer-binding proteins (C/EBPs) are main regulators of adipogenesis.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Comparing with cells from other lineage, the in vitro differentiation of fat cells is authentic and recapitulates most of the characteristic feature of in vivo differentiation.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] The key features of differentiated adipocytes are growth arrest, morphological change, high expression of lipogenic genes and production of adipokines like adiponectin, leptin, resistin (in the mouse, not in humans) and TNF-alpha.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] In vitro studies on differentiation have used the pre-committed preadipocyte lineage, such as 3T3-L1 and 3T3-F442A cell line, or preadipocytes isolated from the stromal-vascular fraction of white adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] In vitro differentiation is a highly ordered process.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Firstly, proliferating preadipocytes arrest growth usually by contact inhibition.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] The growth arrest followed by the earliest events, including a morphological change of preadipocyte from the fibroblast-shape to the round-shape and the induction of transcription factors C/EBPβ, and C/EBPδ.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] The second phase of growth arrest is the expression of two key transcription factors PPARγ and C/EBPα which promote expression of genes that confer the characteristics of mature adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] These genes include adipocyte protein (aP2), insulin receptor, glycerophosphate dehydrogenase, fatty acid synthase, acetyl CoA carboxylase, glucose transporter type 4 (Glut 4) and so on.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Through this process, lipid droplets accumulate in the adipocyte.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] However, preadipocytes cell lines have difficulty differentiating into adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Preadipocytes display CD45− CD31− CD34+ CD29+ SCA1+ CD24+ surface markers can proliferate and differentiate to adipocytes in vivo.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] PPARγ is a member of the nuclear-receptor superfamily and is the master regulator of adipogenesis.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] PPARγ heterodimerizes with retinoid X receptor (RXR) and then binds to DNA, which activates the promoters of the downstream genes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] PPARγ induces fat-cell specific genes, including aP2, adiponectin and phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase (PEPCK).
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] PPARg activation has effects on several aspects of the mature adipocyte characteristics such as morphological changes, lipid accumulation, and the acquisition of insulin sensitivity.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] PPARγ is necessary and sufficient to promote fat cell differentiation.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] PPARγ is required for embryonic stem cells (ES cells) differentiation to adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] The expression of PPARγ itself is sufficient to convert fibroblast into adipocytes in vitro.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Other pro-adipogenic factors like C/EBPs and Krüppel-like factors (KLFs) have been shown to induce the PPARγ promoter.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Moreover, PPARγ is also required to maintain the expression of genes that characterize the mature adipocyte.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Thiazolidinediones (TZDs), antidiabetic agents which well used differentiation cocktail in vitro, promoting the activity of PPARγ.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] C/EBPs, transcription factors, are members of the basic-leucine zipper class. cAMP, an inducer of adipogenesis, can promote expression of C/EBPβ and C/EBPδ.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] At the early stage of differentiation, the transient increase of C/EBPβ and C/EBPδ mRNA and protein levels are thought to activate the adipogenic transcription factors, PPARγ and C/EBPα.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] PPARγ and C/EBPα can feedback to induce the expression of each other as well as their downstream genes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] C/EBPα also plays an important role in the insulin sensitivity of adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] However, C/EBPγ suppresses differentiation which might due to inactivation by C/EBPβ.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Although PPARγ and C/EBPα are master regulators of adipogenesis, other transcription factors function in the progression of differentiation.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] T-cell factor/lymphoid enhancer-binding factor (TCF/LEF), GATA2/3, retinoic acid receptor α, and SMAD6/7 don't affect the expression of C/EBPβ and C/EBPδ but inhibit the induction of PPARγ and C/EBPα.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] TET1 plays an important role in the early stages of adipogenesis.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] During this process, TET1 increases its expression and promotes DNA demethylation.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] This epigenetic modification facilitates the activation of genes required for adipocyte formation.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] In this way, TET1 helps progenitor cells change their identity and acquire the characteristics of mature adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Products of endocrine system such as insulin, IGF-1, cAMP, glucocorticoid, and triiodothyronine effectively induce adipogenesis in preadipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Insulin regulates adipogenesis through insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF1) receptor signaling.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Insulin/IGF1 promotes the induction transcription factors regulating terminal differentiation.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Wnt/β-catenin signaling suppresses adipogenesis, by promoting the differentiation of mesenchymal stem cells into myocytes and osteocytes but blocking the commitment to the adipocytic lineage.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Wnt/β-catenin inhibits the differentiation of preadipocytes by inhibiting the induction of PPARγ and C/EBPα.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Bone morphogenetic proteins (BMPs) are transforming growth factor β (TGFβ) superfamily members.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] BMP2 can either stimulates the determination of multipotent cells or induce osteogenesis through different receptor heteromers.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] BMPs also promotes the differentiation of preadipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Senescent adipose progenitor cells in subcutaneous adipose tissue has been shown to suppress adipogenic differentiation.
[src:adipocyte/adipogenesis] Reduced adipogenesis in obese persons is due to increased senescent cells in adipose tissue rather than reduced numbers of stem/progenitor cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipokine] The **adipokines**, or **adipocytokines** (Greek **adipo-**, fat; **cytos-**, cell; and **-kinos**, movement) are cytokines (cell signaling proteins) secreted by adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipokine] Some contribute to an obesity-related low-grade state of inflammation or to the development of metabolic syndrome, a constellation of diseases including, but not limited to, type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease and atherosclerosis.
[src:adipocyte/adipokine] The first adipokine to be discovered was leptin in 1994.
[src:adipocyte/adipokine] Since that time, hundreds of adipokines have been discovered.
[src:adipocyte/adipokine] Interleukin 8 (IL-8), interleukin 10 (IL-10), interferon gamma (IFN-γ) and inducible protein 10 (IP-10 or CXCL10) have been shown to be associated with excessive body weight.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin is a 244-amino-acid-long polypeptide (protein).
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] It has four distinct regions: The first is a short signal sequence that targets the hormone for secretion outside the cell; next is a short region that varies between species; the third is a 65-amino acid region with similarity to collagenous proteins; the last is a globular domain.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Overall, this protein shows similarity to the complement 1Q factors (C1Q), but when the three-dimensional structure of the globular region was determined, a striking similarity to TNFα was observed, despite unrelated protein sequences.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin is a protein hormone that modulates a number of metabolic processes, including glucose regulation and fatty acid oxidation.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin is secreted from adipose tissue (and also from the placenta in pregnancy) into the bloodstream and is very abundant in plasma relative to many hormones.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] High adiponectin levels correlate with a lower risk of diabetes mellitus type 2.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Plasma levels of adiponectin are lower in obese subjects than in lean subjects.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Many studies have found adiponectin to be inversely correlated with body mass index in patient populations.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] However, a meta analysis was not able to confirm this association in healthy adults.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Circulating adiponectin concentrations increase during caloric restriction in animals and humans, such as in patients with anorexia nervosa.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Furthermore, a 2014 study suggests that adipose tissue within bone marrow, which increases during caloric restriction, contributes to elevated circulating adiponectin in this context.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Transgenic mice with increased adiponectin show reduced adipocyte differentiation and increased energy expenditure associated with mitochondrial uncoupling.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] The hormone plays a role in the suppression of the metabolic derangements that may result in type 2 diabetes, obesity, atherosclerosis, non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) and an independent risk factor for metabolic syndrome.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin in combination with leptin has been shown to completely reverse insulin resistance in mice.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin enhances insulin sensitivity primarily though regulation of fatty acid oxidation and suppression of hepatic glucose production.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin is secreted into the bloodstream, where it accounts for about 0.01% of all plasma protein at around 5-10 μg/mL.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] In adults, plasma concentrations are higher in females than males, and are reduced in diabetics compared to nondiabetics.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Weight reduction significantly increases circulating concentrations.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin automatically self-associates into larger structures.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Initially, three adiponectin molecules bind together to form a homotrimer.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] The trimers continue to self-associate and form hexamers or dodecamers.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Like the plasma concentration, the relative levels of the higher-order structures are sexually dimorphic, where females have increased proportions of the high-molecular-weight forms.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Recent studies showed that the high-molecular-weight form may be the most biologically active form regarding glucose homeostasis.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] High-molecular-weight adiponectin was further found to be associated with a lower risk of diabetes with similar magnitude of association as total adiponectin.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] However, coronary artery disease has been found to be positively associated with high molecular weight adiponectin, but not with low molecular weight adiponectin.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin exerts some of its weight-reduction effects via the brain.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] This is similar to the action of leptin; adiponectin and leptin can act synergistically.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin promoted synaptic and memory function in the brain.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Humans with lower levels of adiponectin have reduced cognitive function.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin binds to a number of receptors.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] These have distinct tissue specificities within the body and have different affinities to the various forms of adiponectin.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] AdipoR1 is enriched in skeletal muscle, whereas AdipoR2 is enriched in liver.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Six months of exercise has been shown in rats to double muscle AdipoR1.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] The receptors affect the downstream target AMP kinase, an important cellular metabolic rate control point.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Expression of the receptors is correlated with insulin levels, as well as reduced in mouse models of diabetes, particularly in skeletal muscle and adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] In 2016, the University of Tokyo announced that it would launch an investigation into claims of fabrication of AdipoR1 and AdipoR2 identification data, as accused by an anonymous person/group called Ordinary_researchers.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin was first characterised in 1995 in differentiating 3T3-L1 adipocytes (Scherer PE et al.).
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] In 1996 it was characterised in mice as the mRNA transcript most highly expressed in adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] In 2007, adiponectin was identified as a transcript highly expressed in preadipocytes (precursors of fat cells) differentiating into adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] The human homologue was identified as the most abundant transcript in adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Contrary to expectations, despite being produced in adipose tissue, adiponectin was found to be decreased in obesity.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] This downregulation has not been fully explained.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] The gene was localised to chromosome 3q27, a region highlighted as affecting genetic susceptibility to type 2 diabetes and obesity.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Supplementation by differing forms of adiponectin was able to improve insulin control, blood glucose and triglyceride levels in mouse models.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] The gene was investigated for variants that predispose to type 2 diabetes.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Several single nucleotide polymorphisms in the coding region and surrounding sequence were identified from several different populations, with varying prevalences, degrees of association and strength of effect on type 2 diabetes.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Berberine, an isoquinoline alkaloid, has been shown to increase adiponectin expression, which partly explains its beneficial effects on metabolic disturbances.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Mice fed the omega-3 fatty acids eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) have shown increased plasma adiponectin.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Curcumin, capsaicin, gingerol, and catechins have also been found to increase adiponectin expression.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Phylogenetic distribution includes expression in birds and fish.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Lower levels of adiponectin are associated with ADHD in adults.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin levels were found to be increased in rheumatoid arthritis patients responding to DMARDs or TNF inhibitor therapy.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] A low adiponectin to leptin ratio has been found in patients with COVID-19 pneumonia compared to healthy controls.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Exercise induced release of adiponectin increased hippocampal growth and led to antidepressive symptoms in mice.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Several studies have found a positive correlation in caffeine consumption and increased adiponectin levels, although the mechanism for this is unknown and requires more research.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Circulating levels of adiponectin can indirectly be increased through lifestyle modifications and certain medications such as statins.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] A small molecule adiponectin receptor AdipoR1 and AdipoR2 agonist, AdipoRon, has been reported.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] In 2016, the University of Tokyo announced it was launching an investigation into anonymously made claims of fabricated and falsified data on AdipoR1, AdipoR2, and AdipoRon.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Extracts of sweet potatoes have been reported to increase levels of adiponectin and thereby improve glycemic control in humans.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] However, a systematic review concluded there is insufficient evidence to support the consumption of sweet potatoes to treat type 2 diabetes mellitus.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin is apparently able to cross the blood-brain-barrier.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] However, conflicting data on this issue exist.
[src:adipocyte/adiponectin] Adiponectin has a half-life of 2.5 hours in humans.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Previously treated as being hormonally inert, in recent years adipose tissue has been recognized as a major endocrine organ, as it produces hormones such as leptin, estrogen, resistin, and cytokines (especially TNFα).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In obesity, adipose tissue is implicated in the chronic release of pro-inflammatory markers known as adipokines, which are responsible for the development of metabolic syndrome—a constellation of diseases including type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease and atherosclerosis.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is derived from preadipocytes and its formation appears to be controlled in part by the adipose gene.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The two types of adipose tissue are white adipose tissue (WAT), which stores energy, and brown adipose tissue (BAT), which generates body heat.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue—more specifically brown adipose tissue—was first identified by the Swiss naturalist Conrad Gessner in 1551.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In humans, adipose tissue is located beneath the skin (subcutaneous fat), around internal organs (visceral fat), in bone marrow (yellow bone marrow), intermuscular (muscular system), and in the breast (breast tissue).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is found in specific locations, which are referred to as *adipose depots*.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In addition to adipocytes, which comprise the highest percentage of cells within adipose tissue, other cell types are present, collectively termed stromal vascular fraction (SVF) of cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] SVF includes preadipocytes, fibroblasts, adipose tissue macrophages, and endothelial cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue contains many small blood vessels.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In the integumentary system, which includes the skin, it accumulates in the deepest level, the subcutaneous layer, providing insulation from heat and cold.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Around organs, it provides protective padding.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Adipose depots in different parts of the body have different biochemical profiles.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Under normal conditions, it provides feedback for hunger and diet to the brain.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In an obese person, excess adipose tissue hanging downward from the abdomen is referred to as a panniculus.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] A panniculus complicates surgery of the morbidly obese individual.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] It may remain as a literal "apron of skin" if a severely obese person loses large amounts of fat (a common result of gastric bypass surgery).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Obesity is treated through exercises, diet, behavioral therapy, and liposuctions.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Reconstructive surgery is one aspect of treatment.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat or abdominal fat (also known as organ fat or intra-abdominal fat) is located inside the abdominal cavity, packed between the organs (stomach, liver, intestines, kidneys, etc.).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is different from subcutaneous fat underneath the skin, and intramuscular fat interspersed in skeletal muscles.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Fat in the lower body, as in thighs and buttocks, is subcutaneous and is not consistently spaced tissue, whereas fat in the abdomen is mostly visceral and semi-fluid.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is composed of several adipose depots, including mesenteric, epididymal white adipose tissue (EWAT), and perirenal depots.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is often expressed in terms of its area in cm2 (VFA, visceral fat area).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] An excess of visceral fat is known as abdominal obesity, or "belly fat", in which the abdomen protrudes excessively.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] New developments such as the Body Volume Index (BVI) are specifically designed to measure abdominal volume and abdominal fat.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Excess visceral fat is also linked to type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance, inflammatory diseases, and other obesity-related diseases.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Likewise, the accumulation of neck fat (or cervical adipose tissue) has been shown to be associated with mortality.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Several studies have suggested that visceral fat can be predicted from simple anthropometric measures, and predicts mortality more accurately than body mass index or waist circumference.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Men are more likely to have fat stored in the abdomen due to sex hormone differences.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Estrogen (female sex hormone) causes fat to be stored in the buttocks, thighs, and hips in women.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] When women reach menopause and the estrogen produced by the ovaries declines, fat migrates from the buttocks, hips and thighs to the waist; later fat is stored in the abdomen.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat can be caused by excess cortisol levels.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] At least 10 MET-hours per week of aerobic exercise leads to visceral fat reduction in those without metabolic-related disorders.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Resistance training and caloric restriction also reduce visceral fat, although their effect may not be cumulative.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Both exercise and hypocaloric diet cause loss of visceral fat, but exercise has a larger effect on visceral fat versus total fat.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] High-intensity exercise is one way to effectively reduce total abdominal fat.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] An energy-restricted diet combined with exercise will reduce total body fat and the ratio of visceral adipose tissue to subcutaneous adipose tissue, suggesting a preferential mobilization for visceral fat over subcutaneous fat.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Epicardial adipose tissue (EAT) is a particular form of visceral fat deposited around the heart and found to be a metabolically active organ that generates various bioactive molecules, which might significantly affect cardiac function.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Marked component differences have been observed in comparing EAT with subcutaneous fat, suggesting a location-specific impact of stored fatty acids on adipocyte function and metabolism.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Most of the remaining nonvisceral fat is found just below the skin in a region called the hypodermis.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] This subcutaneous fat is not related to many of the classic obesity-related pathologies, such as heart disease, cancer, and stroke, and some evidence even suggests it might be protective.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The typically female (or gynecoid) pattern of body fat distribution around the hips, thighs, and buttocks is subcutaneous fat, and therefore poses less of a health risk compared to visceral fat.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Like all other fat organs, subcutaneous fat is an active part of the endocrine system, secreting the hormones leptin and resistin.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The relationship between the subcutaneous adipose layer and total body fat in a person is often modelled by using regression equations.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The most popular of these equations was formed by Durnin and Wormersley, who rigorously tested many types of skinfold, and, as a result, created two formulae to calculate the body density of both men and women.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] These equations present an inverse correlation between skinfolds and body density—as the sum of skinfolds increases, the body density decreases.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Factors such as sex, age, population size or other variables may make the equations invalid and unusable, and, as of 2012, Durnin and Wormersley's equations remain only estimates of a person's true level of fatness.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Marrow fat, also known as marrow adipose tissue (MAT), is a poorly understood adipose depot that resides in the bone and is interspersed with hematopoietic cells as well as bony elements.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The adipocytes in this depot are derived from mesenchymal stem cells (MSC) which can give rise to fat cells, bone cells as well as other cell types.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The fact that MAT increases in the setting of calorie restriction/ anorexia is a feature that distinguishes this depot from other fat depots.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Exercise regulates MAT, decreasing MAT quantity and diminishing the size of marrow adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The exercise regulation of marrow fat suggests that it bears some physiologic similarity to other white adipose depots.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Moreover, increased MAT in obesity further suggests a similarity to white fat depots.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Ectopic fat is the storage of triglycerides in tissues other than adipose tissue, that are supposed to contain only small amounts of fat, such as the liver, skeletal muscle, heart, and pancreas.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] This can interfere with cellular functions and hence organ function and is associated with insulin resistance in type-2 diabetes.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] It is stored in relatively high amounts around the organs of the abdominal cavity, but is not to be confused with visceral fat.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The specific cause for the accumulation of ectopic fat is unknown.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The cause is likely a combination of genetic, environmental, and behavioral factors that are involved in excess energy intake and decreased physical activity.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Substantial weight loss can reduce ectopic fat stores in all organs and this is associated with an improvement of the function of those organs.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In the latter case, non-invasive weight loss interventions like diet or exercise can decrease ectopic fat (particularly in heart and liver) in overweight or obese children and adults.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Free fatty acids (FFAs) are liberated from lipoproteins by lipoprotein lipase (LPL) and enter the adipocyte, where they are reassembled into triglycerides by esterifying them onto glycerol.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Human fat tissue contains from 61% to 94% lipids.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Lean and obese individuals tend towards the low and high ends of this range, respectively.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] There is a constant flux of FFAs entering and leaving adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The net direction of this flux is controlled by insulin and leptin—if insulin is elevated, then there is a net inward flux of FFA, and only when insulin is low can FFA leave adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Insulin secretion is stimulated by high blood sugar, which results from consuming carbohydrates.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In humans, lipolysis (hydrolysis of triglycerides into free fatty acids) is controlled through the balanced control of lipolytic B-adrenergic receptors and a2A-adrenergic receptor-mediated antilipolysis.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Fat cells have an important physiological role in maintaining triglyceride and free fatty acid levels, as well as determining insulin resistance.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Abdominal fat has a different metabolic profile—being more prone to induce insulin resistance.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] This explains to a large degree why central obesity is a marker of impaired glucose tolerance and is an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease (even in the absence of diabetes mellitus and hypertension).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Recent advances in biotechnology have allowed for the harvesting of adult stem cells from adipose tissue, allowing stimulation of tissue regrowth using a patient's own cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In addition, adipose-derived stem cells from both human and animals reportedly can be efficiently reprogrammed into induced pluripotent stem cells without the need for feeder cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The use of a patient's own cells reduces the chance of tissue rejection and avoids ethical issues associated with the use of human embryonic stem cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] A growing body of evidence also suggests that different fat depots (i.e. abdominal, omental, pericardial) yield adipose-derived stem cells with different characteristics.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] These depot-dependent features include proliferation rate, immunophenotype, differentiation potential, gene expression, as well as sensitivity to hypoxic culture conditions.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Oxygen levels seem to play an important role on the metabolism and in general the function of adipose-derived stem cells.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is a major peripheral source of aromatase in both males and females, contributing to the production of estradiol.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissues also secrete a type of cytokines (cell-to-cell signalling proteins) called adipokines (adipose cytokines), which play a role in obesity-associated complications.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Perivascular adipose tissue releases adipokines such as adiponectin that affect the contractile function of the vessels that they surround.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Brown fat or brown adipose tissue (BAT) is a specialized form of adipose tissue important for adaptive thermogenesis in humans and other mammals.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] BAT can generate heat by "uncoupling" the respiratory chain of oxidative phosphorylation within mitochondria through tissue-specific expression of uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] BAT is primarily located around the neck and large blood vessels of the thorax, where it may effectively act in heat exchange.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] BAT is robustly activated upon cold exposure by the release of catecholamines from sympathetic nerves that results in UCP1 activation.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Nearly half of the nerves present in adipose tissue are sensory neurons connected to the dorsal root ganglia.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] BAT activation may also occur in response to overfeeding.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] UCP1 activity is stimulated by long chain fatty acids that are produced subsequent to β-adrenergic receptor activation.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] UCP1 is proposed to function as a fatty acid proton symporter, although the exact mechanism has yet to be elucidated.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In contrast, UCP1 is inhibited by ATP, ADP, and GTP.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Attempts to simulate this process pharmacologically have so far been unsuccessful.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Techniques to manipulate the differentiation of "brown fat" could become a mechanism for weight loss therapy in the future, encouraging the growth of tissue with this specialized metabolism without inducing it in other organs.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] A review on the eventual therapeutic targeting of brown fat to treat human obesity was published by Samuelson and Vidal-Puig in 2020.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Until recently, brown adipose tissue in humans was thought to be primarily limited to infants, but new evidence has overturned that belief.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Metabolically active tissue with temperature responses similar to brown adipose was first reported in the neck and trunk of some human adults in 2007, and the presence of brown adipose in human adults was later verified histologically in the same anatomical regions.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Browning of WAT, also referred to as "beiging", occurs when adipocytes within WAT depots develop features of BAT.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] **Beige adipocytes** take on a multilocular appearance (containing several lipid droplets) and increase expression of uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In doing so, these normally energy-storing adipocytes become energy-releasing adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The calorie-burning capacity of brown and beige fat has been extensively studied as research efforts focus on therapies targeted to treat obesity and diabetes.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The drug 2,4-dinitrophenol, which also acts as a chemical uncoupler similarly to UCP1, was used for weight loss in the 1930s.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] However, it was quickly discontinued when excessive dosing led to adverse side effects including hyperthermia and death. β3-adrenergic agonists, like CL316,243, have also been developed and tested in humans.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] However, the use of such drugs has proven largely unsuccessful due to several challenges, including varying species receptor specificity and poor oral bioavailability.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Cold is a primary regulator of BAT processes and induces WAT browning.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Browning in response to chronic cold exposure has been well documented and is a reversible process.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] A study in mice demonstrated that cold-induced browning can be completely reversed in 21 days, with measurable decreases in UCP1 seen within a 24-hour period.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] A study by Rosenwald et al. revealed that when the animals are re-exposed to a cold environment, the same adipocytes will adopt a beige phenotype, suggesting that beige adipocytes are retained.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Transcriptional regulators, as well as a growing number of other factors, regulate the induction of beige fat.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Four regulators of transcription are central to WAT browning and serve as targets for many of the molecules known to influence this process.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] These include peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARγ), PRDM16, peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma coactivator 1 alpha (PGC-1α), and Early B-Cell Factor-2 (EBF2).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The list of molecules that influence browning has grown in direct proportion to the popularity of this topic and is constantly evolving as more knowledge is acquired.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Among these molecules are irisin and fibroblast growth factor 21 (FGF21), which have been well-studied and are believed to be important regulators of browning.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Irisin is secreted from muscle in response to exercise and has been shown to increase browning by acting on beige preadipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] FGF21, a hormone secreted mainly by the liver, has garnered a great deal of interest after being identified as a potent stimulator of glucose uptake and a browning regulator through its effects on PGC-1α.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] It is increased in BAT during cold exposure and is thought to aid in resistance to diet-induced obesity FGF21 may also be secreted in response to exercise and a low protein diet, although the latter has not been thoroughly investigated.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Data from these studies suggest that environmental factors like diet and exercise may be important mediators of browning.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In mice, it was found that beiging can occur through the production of methionine-enkephalin peptides by type 2 innate lymphoid cells in response to interleukin 33.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Due to the complex nature of adipose tissue and a growing list of browning regulatory molecules, great potential exists for the use of bioinformatics tools to improve study within this field.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Studies of WAT browning have greatly benefited from advances in these techniques, as beige fat is rapidly gaining popularity as a therapeutic target for the treatment of obesity and diabetes.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] DNA microarray is a bioinformatics tool used to quantify expression levels of various genes simultaneously, and has been used extensively in the study of adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] One such study used microarray analysis in conjunction with Ingenuity IPA software to look at changes in WAT and BAT gene expression when mice were exposed to temperatures of 28 and 6 °C.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The most significantly up- and downregulated genes were then identified and used for analysis of differentially expressed pathways.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] It was discovered that many of the pathways upregulated in WAT after cold exposure are also highly expressed in BAT, such as oxidative phosphorylation, fatty acid metabolism, and pyruvate metabolism.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] This suggests that some of the adipocytes switched to a beige phenotype at 6 °C.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Mössenböck et al. also used microarray analysis to demonstrate that insulin deficiency inhibits the differentiation of beige adipocytes but does not disturb their capacity for browning.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] These two studies demonstrate the potential for the use of microarray in the study of WAT browning.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] RNA sequencing (RNA-Seq) is a powerful computational tool that allows for the quantification of RNA expression for all genes within a sample.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Incorporating RNA-Seq into browning studies is of great value, as it offers better specificity, sensitivity, and a more comprehensive overview of gene expression than other methods.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] RNA-Seq has been used in both human and mouse studies in an attempt characterize beige adipocytes according to their gene expression profiles and to identify potential therapeutic molecules that may induce the beige phenotype.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] One such study used RNA-Seq to compare gene expression profiles of WAT from wild-type (WT) mice and those overexpressing Early B-Cell Factor-2 (EBF2).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] WAT from the transgenic animals exhibited a brown fat gene program and had decreased WAT specific gene expression compared to the WT mice.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Thus, EBF2 has been identified as a potential therapeutic molecule to induce beiging.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Chromatin immunoprecipitation with sequencing (ChIP-seq) is a method used to identify protein binding sites on DNA and assess histone modifications.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] This tool has enabled examination of epigenetic regulation of browning and helps elucidate the mechanisms by which protein-DNA interactions stimulate the differentiation of beige adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Studies observing the chromatin landscapes of beige adipocytes have found that adipogenesis of these cells results from the formation of cell specific chromatin landscapes, which regulate the transcriptional program and, ultimately, control differentiation.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Using ChIP-seq in conjunction with other tools, recent studies have identified over 30 transcriptional and epigenetic factors that influence beige adipocyte development.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The thrifty gene hypothesis (also called the famine hypothesis) states that in some populations the body would be more efficient at retaining fat in times of plenty, thereby endowing greater resistance to starvation in times of food scarcity.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In 1995, Jeffrey Friedman, in his residency at the Rockefeller University, together with Rudolph Leibel, Douglas Coleman et al. discovered the protein leptin that the genetically obese mouse lacked.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Leptin is produced in the white adipose tissue and signals to the hypothalamus.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] When leptin levels drop, the body interprets this as a loss of energy, and hunger increases.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Mice lacking this protein eat until they are four times their normal size.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Leptin, however, plays a different role in diet-induced obesity in rodents and humans.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Because adipocytes produce leptin, leptin levels are elevated in the obese.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] However, hunger remains, and—when leptin levels drop due to weight loss—hunger increases.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The drop of leptin is better viewed as a starvation signal than the rise of leptin as a satiety signal.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] However, elevated leptin in obesity is known as leptin resistance.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The changes that occur in the hypothalamus to result in leptin resistance in obesity are currently the focus of obesity research.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Gene defects in the leptin gene (*ob*) are rare in human obesity.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Others have been identified as genetically partially deficient in leptin, and, in these individuals, leptin levels on the low end of the normal range can predict obesity.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Several mutations of genes involving the melanocortins (used in brain signaling associated with appetite) and their receptors have also been identified as causing obesity in a larger portion of the population than leptin mutations.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Different cell types within adipose tissue exhibit distinct DNA methylation patterns.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Mature adipocytes and adipose progenitor cells (ASPCs) show a high degree of hypomethylation, affecting more than 50% of their regulatory regions.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] This hypomethylation is associated with the activation of genes involved in triglyceride synthesis, such as glycerol‑3‑phosphate acyltransferase 1 (GPAM).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In contrast, myeloid cells display approximately 73% hypermethylated regions, reflecting an epigenetic program opposite to that of the adipocytic lineage.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Overall, there is a direct relationship between DNA demethylation and gene expression, whereby highly expressed genes tend to exhibit low methylation levels.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] These epigenetic patterns contribute to defining the functional identity of the different cell types within subcutaneous adipose tissue (SAT).
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue has a density of ~0.9 g/ml.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Thus, a person with more adipose tissue will float more easily than a person of the same weight with more muscular tissue, since muscular tissue has a density of 1.06 g/ml.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In addition to the visible changes in adipose tissue associated with obesity, recent research indicates that the risk of developing abdominal obesity and cardiometabolic alterations also depends on the 3D organization of the genome in subcutaneous adipose tissue.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Single‑cell epigenomic studies have shown that many genetic variants associated with abdominal fat distribution (measured as WHRadjBMI) are preferentially located in active genomic regions of adipocytes.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] These regions display low levels of DNA methylation and belong to the so‑called A compartment, which is characterized by higher gene activity.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] These findings suggest that adipocytes in subcutaneous adipose tissue play a key role in mediating the genetic risk associated with abdominal obesity.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] A **body fat meter** is a tool used to measure the body fat to weight ratio in the human body.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Different meters use various methods to determine the ratio.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] They tend to under-read body fat percentage.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] In contrast with clinical tools like DXA and underwater weighing, one relatively inexpensive type of body fat meter uses the principle of bioelectrical impedance analysis (BIA) in order to determine an individual's body fat percentage.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] To achieve this, the meter passes a small, harmless, electric current through the body and measures the resistance, then uses information on the person's weight, height, age, and sex to calculate an approximate value for the person's body fat percentage.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The calculation measures the total volume of water in the body (lean tissue and muscle contain a higher percentage of water than fat), and estimates the percentage of fat based on this information.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] The result can fluctuate several percentage points depending on what has been eaten and how much water has been drunk before the analysis.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] This method is quick and readily accessible, but imprecise.
[src:adipocyte/adipose-tissue] Alternative methods are: skin fold methods using calipers, underwater weighing, whole body air displacement plethysmography (ADP) and DXA.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] A histological scope of anatomical terminology describes structure, layout and position more precisely and mitigates ambiguity.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] An internationally accepted lexicon is Terminologia Histologica.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] Epithelium can be arranged in a single layer of cells described as "simple", or more than one layer, described as "stratified".
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] However, when taller simple columnar epithelial cells are viewed in cross section showing several nuclei appearing at different heights, they can be confused with stratified epithelia.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] This kind of epithelium is therefore described as pseudostratified columnar epithelium.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] Transitional epithelium has cells that can change from squamous to cuboidal, depending on the amount of tension on the epithelium.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] A **mucous membrane** or **mucosa** is a membrane that lines various cavities in the body and covers the surface of internal organs.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] It consists of one or more layers of epithelial cells overlying a layer of loose connective tissue.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] It is mostly of endodermal origin and is continuous with the skin at various body openings such as the eyes, ears, inside the nose, inside the mouth, lip, the urethral opening and the anus.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] Some mucous membranes secrete mucus, a thick protective fluid.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The function of the membrane is to stop pathogens and dirt from entering the body and to prevent bodily tissues from becoming dehydrated.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The submucosa consists of a dense and irregular layer of connective tissue with blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves branching into the mucosa and muscular layer.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] It contains the submucous plexus, and enteric nervous plexus, situated on the inner surface of the muscular layer.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The muscular layer (also known as the *muscularis propria* ) consists of two layers of muscle, the inner and outer layer.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The muscle of the inner layer is arranged in circular rings around the tract, whereas the muscle of the outer layer is arranged longitudinally.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The stomach has an extra layer, an inner oblique muscular layer.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] Between the two muscle layers are the myenteric or Auerbach's plexus.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] Activity is initiated by the pacemaker cells (interstitial cells of Cajal).
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The gut has intrinsic peristaltic activity (basal electrical rhythm) due to its self-contained enteric nervous system.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The rate can of course be modulated by the rest of the autonomic nervous system.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The layers are not truly longitudinal or circular, rather the layers of muscle are helical with different pitches.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The inner circular is helical with a steep pitch and the outer longitudinal is helical with a much shallower pitch.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The hollow inner part of a body organ (such as the gastrointestinal tract) or tube (such as an artery) is called the *lumen*.
[src:adipocyte/anatomical-terms-of-microanatomy] The side of a cell facing the lumen is called the **apical** surface; the opposite side, facing away from the lumen is the *basolateral* surface, which faces instead towards the *interstitium*, and away from the lumen.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] An **androgen** (from Greek *andr-*, the stem of the word meaning 'man') is any natural or synthetic steroid hormone that regulates the development and maintenance of male physiological characteristics in vertebrates by binding to androgen receptors.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] This includes the embryological development of the primary male sex organs, and the development of male secondary sex characteristics at puberty.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens are synthesized in the testes, the ovaries, and the adrenal glands.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens increase in both males and females during puberty.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] The major androgen in males is testosterone.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Dihydrotestosterone (DHT) and androstenedione are of equal importance in male development.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] DHT *in utero* causes differentiation of the penis, scrotum and prostate.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] In adulthood, DHT contributes to balding, prostate growth, and sebaceous gland activity.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Although androgens are commonly thought of only as male sex hormones, females also have them, but at lower levels: they function in libido and sexual arousal.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens are the precursors to estrogens in all humans.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] In addition to their role as natural hormones, androgens are used as medications; for information on androgens as medications, see the androgen replacement therapy and anabolic steroid articles.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] The main subset of androgens, known as adrenal androgens, is composed of 19-carbon steroids synthesized in the zona reticularis, the innermost layer of the adrenal cortex.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Adrenal androgens function as weak steroids (though some are precursors), and the subset includes dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA), dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate (DHEA-S), androstenedione (A4), and androstenediol (A5).
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Determined by consideration of all biological assay methods (c.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] The ovaries and adrenal glands also produce androgens, but at much lower levels than the testes.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] During mammalian development, the gonads are at first capable of becoming either ovaries or testes.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] In humans, starting at about week 4, the gonadal rudiments are present within the intermediate mesoderm adjacent to the developing kidneys.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] At about week 6, epithelial sex cords develop within the forming testes and incorporate the germ cells as they migrate into the gonads.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] In males, certain Y chromosome genes, particularly SRY, control development of the male phenotype, including conversion of the early bipotential gonad into testes.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] In males, the sex cords fully invade the developing gonads.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] The mesoderm-derived epithelial cells of the sex cords in developing testes become the Sertoli cells, which will function to support sperm cell formation.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] A minor population of nonepithelial cells appear between the tubules by week 8 of human fetal development.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Soon after they differentiate, Leydig cells begin to produce androgens.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] The androgens function as paracrine hormones required by the Sertoli cells to support sperm production.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] They are also required for the masculinization of the developing male fetus (including penis and scrotum formation).
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Under the influence of androgens, remnants of the mesonephron, the Wolffian ducts, develop into the epididymis, vas deferens and seminal vesicles.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] This action of androgens is supported by a hormone from Sertoli cells, Müllerian inhibitory hormone (MIH), which prevents the embryonic Müllerian ducts from developing into fallopian tubes and other female reproductive tract tissues in male embryos.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] MIH and androgens cooperate to allow for movement of testes into the scrotum.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Before the production of the pituitary hormone luteinizing hormone (LH) by the embryo starting at about weeks 11–12, human chorionic gonadotrophin (hCG) promotes the differentiation of Leydig cells and their production of androgens at week 8.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgen action in target tissues often involves conversion of testosterone to 5α-dihydrotestosterone (DHT).
[src:adipocyte/androgen] At the time of puberty, androgen levels increase dramatically in males, and androgens mediate the development of masculine secondary sexual characteristics as well as the activation of spermatogenesis and fertility and masculine behavioral changes such as increased sex drive.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Masculine secondary sexual characteristics include androgenic hair, voice deepening, emergence of the Adam's apple, broadening of the shoulders, increased muscle mass, and penile growth.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] During puberty, androgen, LH and follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) production increase and the sex cords hollow out, forming the seminiferous tubules, and the germ cells start to differentiate into sperm.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Throughout adulthood, androgens and FSH cooperatively act on Sertoli cells in the testes to support sperm production.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Exogenous androgen supplements can be used as a male contraceptive.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Elevated androgen levels caused by use of androgen supplements can inhibit production of LH and block production of endogenous androgens by Leydig cells.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Without the locally high levels of androgens in testes due to androgen production by Leydig cells, the seminiferous tubules can degenerate, resulting in infertility.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] For this reason, many transdermal androgen patches are applied to the scrotum.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Males typically have less body fat than females.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Recent results indicate androgens inhibit the ability of some fat cells to store lipids by blocking a signal transduction pathway that normally supports adipocyte function.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Males typically have more skeletal muscle mass than females.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens promote the enlargement of skeletal muscle cells in a coordinated manner by acting on several cell types in skeletal muscle tissue.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] One cell type, called the myoblast, conveys androgen receptors for generating muscle.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Fusion of myoblasts generates myotubes, in a process linked to androgen receptor levels.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Higher androgen levels lead to increased expression of androgen receptor.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Circulating levels of androgens can influence human behavior because some neurons are sensitive to steroid hormones.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgen levels have been implicated in the regulation of human aggression and libido.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Indeed, androgens are capable of altering the structure of the brain in several species, including mice, rats, and primates, producing sex differences.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] More recent studies showing the general mood of transgender men, who have undergone transgender hormone replacement therapy replacing estrogens with androgens, do not show any substantial long-term behavioral changes.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Numerous reports have shown androgens alone are capable of altering the structure of the brain, but identification of which alterations in neuroanatomy stem from androgens or estrogens is difficult, because of their potential for conversion.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Evidence from neurogenesis (formation of new neurons) studies on male rats has shown that the hippocampus is a useful brain region to examine when determining the effects of androgens on behavior.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] To examine neurogenesis, wild-type male rats were compared with male rats that had androgen insensitivity syndrome, a genetic difference resulting in complete or partial insensitivity to androgens and a lack of external male genitalia.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Neural injections of bromodeoxyuridine (BrdU) were applied to males of both groups to test for neurogenesis.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Analysis showed that testosterone and dihydrotestosterone regulated adult hippocampal neurogenesis (AHN).
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Adult hippocampal neurogenesis was regulated through the androgen receptor in the wild-type male rats, but not in the TMF male rats.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] To further test the role of activated androgen receptors on AHN, flutamide, an antiandrogen drug that competes with testosterone and dihydrotestosterone for androgen receptors, and dihydrotestosterone were administered to normal male rats.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Dihydrotestosterone increased the number of BrdU cells, while flutamide inhibited these cells.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] This research demonstrates how androgens can increase AHN.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Researchers also examined how mild exercise affected androgen synthesis which in turn causes AHN activation of *N*-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] NMDA induces a calcium flux that allows for synaptic plasticity which is crucial for AHN.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Researchers injected both orchidectomized (ORX) (castrated) and sham castrated male rats with BrdU to determine if the number of new cells was increased.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] They found that AHN in male rats is increased with mild exercise by boosting synthesis of dihydrotestosterone in the hippocampus.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Again it was noted that AHN was not increased via activation of the estrogen receptors.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgen regulation decreases the likelihood of depression in males.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] In preadolescent male rats, neonatal rats treated with flutamide developed more depression-like symptoms compared to control rats.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Again BrdU was injected into both groups of rats in order to see if cells were multiplying in the living tissue.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] These results demonstrate how the organization of androgens has a positive effect on preadolescent hippocampal neurogenesis that may be linked with lower depression-like symptoms.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Social isolation has a hindering effect in AHN whereas normal regulation of androgens increases AHN.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] A study using male rats showed that testosterone may block social isolation, which results in hippocampal neurogenesis reaching homeostasis—regulation that keeps internal conditions stable.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] A Brdu analysis showed that excess testosterone did not increase this blocking effect against social isolation; that is, the natural circulating levels of androgens cancel out the negative effects of social isolation on AHN.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens have potential roles in relaxation of the myometrium via non-genomic, androgen receptor-independent pathways, preventing premature uterine contractions in pregnancy.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Reduced ability of an XY-karyotype fetus to respond to androgens can result in one of several conditions, including infertility and several forms of intersex conditions.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Yolk androgen levels in certain birds have been positively correlated to social dominance later in life.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens bind to and activate androgen receptors (ARs) to mediate most of their biological effects.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] The reported relative potency varies from source to source.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] The following table is based on (recombinant rat) androgen receptor affinities.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Some weak androgens can be converted to more potent androgens in the body, in particular testosterone and DHT, so they may have additional indirect potency when taken as a drug.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] 5α-Dihydrotestosterone (DHT) was 2.4 times more potent than testosterone at maintaining normal prostate weight and duct lumen mass (this is a measure of epithelial cell function stimulation).
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Whereas DHT was equally potent as testosterone at preventing prostate cell death after castration.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] One of the 11-oxygenated androgens, namely 11-ketotestosterone, has the same potency as testosterone.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens have also been found to signal through membrane androgen receptors, which are distinct from the classical nuclear androgen receptor.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens are synthesized from cholesterol and are produced primarily in the gonads (testicles and ovaries) and also in the adrenal glands.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] The testicles produce a much higher quantity than the ovaries.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Conversion of testosterone to the more potent DHT occurs in prostate gland, liver, brain and skin.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Androgens are metabolized mainly in the liver.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] A low testosterone level (hypogonadism) in men may be treated with testosterone administration.
[src:adipocyte/androgen] Prostate cancer may be treated by removing the major source of testosterone: testicle removal (orchiectomy); or agents which block androgens from accessing their receptor: antiandrogens.
